value.value: The fat body cells, or trophocytes, of fully grown larvae of Aedes aegypti and Culex pipiens are packed with lipid droplets, glycogen granules and vesicles which possibly contain protein, reserves which are carried over to the adult stage. The extent of the reserves depends upon the quality of larval nutrition, and there is some variability betweeen species in the proportions of glycogen and lipid. Unlike the higher Diptera, mosquito adults do not develop and 'adult fat body' differing in structure from that of the larvae. In well-nourished adults the fat body contains deposits of glycogen and lipid but no protein-containing vesicles.
In behavioural terms, aggregation is a congregation of animals that does not depend upon social attraction. Such behaviours are due to the fact that most habitats are not uniform.

definition.value: Aggregation is the irregular distribution of animals between habitats or, more usually, within habitats. Analysis of samples obtained from transects across a habitat reveals a clumped distribution if the ratio of variance to mean is significantly greater then one.

value.value: The attack and consumption of conspecific larvae of the same or an earlier instar.
The presence of a predator has a damping effect on larvae movement. But at higher predator densities larval movement increased again slightly, possibly due to disturbance by the predators.

definition.value: Experiments were conductided with the usage of Aedes aegypti and Culex pipiens larvae and Notonecta undulata.

value.value: The larvae and pupae of some culicuds are able to lighten or darken their body colour in accordance with the lightness or darkness of the background; others lack this ability.
This is an important form of predator avoidance. A variety of relatively safe niches can be discerned among ground waters.

definition.value: Mosquito larval habitats fall into two distinct classes: Phytotelmata and ground waters. Phytotelmata are bodies of water held in or upon parts of terrestrial plants. The greatest variety of phytotelmata occurs in the tropics. Ground waters are also of many types but are predominantly still waters. Whereas most phytotelmata are enclosed water bodies, most natural ground waters are open. The activities of human populations result in the appearance of new habitats colonized by mosquitoes.

value.value: The "grooming" of other individuals has been considered a form of aggresive behaviour and an aspect of feeding.

definition.value: It is unfortunate that we have little or no knowledge of the microorganisms and non-living, particulate matter abhering to the body surface of mosquito larvae in their natural habitats.

value.value: While in depth, a larva remains motionless, often when near or underneath a leaf.
Behavioural patterns of gravid females that result in arrival at potential oviposition sites and indicate the suitability of such sites are termed pre-oviposition behaviour.
During growth the larval stage the alimentary canal grows in cell size and with the formation of polytene and endopolyploid nuclei.
The antennal centres grow slowly compared to the brain as a whole during the larval stage (k=0,8) and very rapidly about the time of larval-pupal ecdysis (k=4).

label.value: development of the central body of the nervous system

value.value: The central body grows most actively in the 4th instar (k=2).
The mushroom bodies grow less strongly than the brain as a whole during the larval stage (k=0,5-0,9) but much more strongly in the pupal stage (k=1,8).
The phenol oxidase enzymes are thought to be central to melanin formation. During encapsulation, polyphenol derivates probably cross-link with proteins from the haemolymph and haemocytes.

In most arthropodes encapsulation is initiated when granular haemocytes degranulate upon contact with foreign bodies, and release components of a phenoloxidase-activating system which adhere to them. Plasmatocytes then enclose the foreign objects within an envelope of hihgly flattened cells which becomes pigmented.

Ovulation is defined as the extrusion of mature oocytes from the ovarian follicles into the calyces and oviducts. Ovulated oocytes enter the vagina, from which they are extruded through the gonotreme at oviposition. Sperm penetrate an oocyte while it is within the vagina. Very soon after oviposition the oocyte chromosomes complete meiosis, and at that stage the oocyte is considered to have transformed into an egg.

Great changes take place in the muscular system during metamorphosis. Most larval head muscles are histolysed but some are carried over to the adult, developing the fine structure of adult muscle and aquiring new relationships with different parts of the head. New muscles arise and the sides and floor of the head become traversed by belts of small myoblasts whose origin is uncertain.

label.value: metamorphosis of the muscles of the thorax and abdomen

value.value: The muscles of the thorax and abdomen are carried over to the adult but the main part of the adult thoracic musculature is new, including the muscles of the appendages, largely formed within the imaginal buds, and the indirect flight muscles. The larval abdominal muscles degenerate early in adult life, having been used for swimming by the pupa and pharate adult. Movements of the adult abdomen are due to small adult muscles which develop from myoblasts in the pupa. Histolysis of the musculature, as of other organs, takes place entirely by autolysis and without the intervention of phagocytes.

Sexual dimorphism in adult mosquitoes is expressed in a number of ways: (i) in the structure of the gonads; (ii) in th eprimary sexual characters which are derived from the genital imaginal disks; and (iii) in secondary sexual characters such as the adult antennae, maxillary palps and body size. Innate behavioural differences between the sexes reflets dimorphism in the structure and function of the nervous system.

label.value: kinetic response to food and dissolved nutrient

value.value: Mosquito larvae accumulate in regions where there is food because they make an orthokinetic response to soluble contituents diffusing from the food.
Inhibition of movement in response to contact stimuli.

It has been observed in Anopheles maculipennis and Anopheles messeae larvae in the laboratory. If exposed to bright light, fourth instar larvae moved about incessantly at the water surface and dived frequently. When by chance they entered a shaded part of the container they became inactive; as a result, almost all larvae congregated in the shade.

Arrestant is substance that induces animals to remain in its presense through their undirected kinetic responses, either by stopping their locomotion (orthokinesis), or changing their rate of turning (klinokinesis).
Attractan is substance that induces animals to make oriented movements towards its source.
A larva spontaneously separates itself from the water surface and descends with a swimming component.
A submerged larva, while feeding, moves anteriorly propelled by currents generated by the actions of its mouthparts.
Tactic responses to chemical compounds.
Tactical responses to gravitation.
Tactic responses to light.
Is described as a tendency to maintain bodily contact with solid objects.

definition.value: Anopheles larvae exhibit this behaviour. In fact, they exhibit negative thigmotaxis; locomotion is reduced by contact with a solid object.

value.value: During successive ovarian cycles the fat body passes through a parallel series of cyclesof ultrastructural generation and degeneration, during each of which the fat body cells or trophocytes exhibit three stages: (i) A previtellogenic stage of activity. (ii) A vitellogenic stage. (iii) A termination stage.
In newly emerged females the cytoplasm of each trophocyte was rich in reserves, containing lipid droplets, glycogen bodies, and three types of membrane-bounded protein granule.

definition.value: During the first three days after emergence the nucleolus grew >3-fold and its enlarging granular component came to contain many maturing pre-ribosomes. The number of ribosomes in the cytoplasm increased sharply. Rough endoplasmic reticulum appeared in the form of cisternae,located in rows, Conentric circles or round lipid inclusions. The Golgi complexes developed into well-defined organelles consisting of small vesicles, 3-4 short vesicular cisternae, and a few larger vesicles. The plasma membrane bacame extended into numerous infoldings, increasing its surface area.

value.value: During this stage, the nucleolus became more multilobed, ribosome proliferation had been renewed, and the rough endoplasmic reticulum was undergoin reorganization.

Termination of vitellogenin synthesis starts with a sharp decline in the concentration of vitellogenin in the fat body. This decline is thought to be associated with a simultaneous and dramatic rise in lysosomal activity.

definition.value: Ultrastructural studies showed that two processes were involved: (i) autophagy, which involved the sequestration of organelles by isolation membranes, followed by fusion of the so-formed isolation body with primary lysosomes; and (ii) crinophagy, which involved the direct fusion of organelles with primary lysosomes.

value.value: During the privitellogenic phase of each ovarian cycle the fat body is made competent for vitellogenin synthesis. Stimulated by juvenile hormone, the trophocytes bacame polyploid and their nucleoli enlarge.

The mechanism regulating termination of vitellogenin synthesis remains to be fully elucidated. Lysosomal degradation causes the termination but whether this is programmed solely by the fat body or whether other factors are involved remain uncertain.

Flight-activity periodicties that had been entrained by photoperiod free-ran in DD or LL, and therefore were endogenously controlled rhythms. The same was observed for the erection of male antennal fibrillae and male responsiveness to the female flight tone, for the responsiveness of females to host cues, and for oviposition activity.
When kept with prey in small containers, Toxorhynchites fourth instar larvae that have reached an advanced stage of development stop feeding but continue killing.

label.value: onset of immediate inhibition of responsiveness

value.value: Culicine females that have engorged fully usually become inactive and non-responsive to host cues.

definition.value: When females of Aedes aegypti were exposed to host odour within 1h of taking a blood meal, those that imbibed 2,5 micro litre blood, or less, remained fully responsive. Responsiveness was negatively correlated with bloodmeal volume within the range 2.5-4 micro litre.

label.value: onset of delayed inhibition of responsiveness

value.value: Non-immediate blocking of responsiveness to host cues. Females remained responsive to host odour for 24h after receiving a 1 micro litre blood enema.

definition.value:
Ovary development occured in many of these females, and from about 30 h after receiving the enema, those that developed ovaries failed to respond to host odour.
The onset and termination of delayed inhibiton are affected by insemination and ovipostion, and the mechanisms that regulate it involve haemolymph-borne factors.

value.value: The reversible change in sensitivity of the lactic acid-sensitive neurones can account for the switching between host-finding and non-host-finding.

Injection of picorgram quantities of 20-hydroxyecdysone into ovariectomized females of Aedes aegypti after blood-feeding caused a significant decrease in responsiveness to host cues when tested 72 h after blood-feeding, provided the females had been inseminated and were not deprived of sucrose.
The fat body is the source of a factor that can induce the reduction in sensitivity of the LA-excited neurones.

definition.value: That the fat body can be the source of such a factor was shown by transplanting, into sugar-fed females, fat body from females that had blood-fed 24 h previously. Twenty-four hours later the recipintes lacked highly sensitive LA-excited neurones, and had become significantly less responsive to host odour. We do not know what factor acts directly on the LA-excited neurones.

label.value: recovery of responsiveness to host cue

value.value: The return of sensitivity to host cues.
The outward expression of an internal oscillator system that entrains to significant 24h oscillations in the external environment.

definition.value: The activity patterns of wild mosquitoes have a phase relationship with the natural cycle of light and darkness. The times of activity of some species fall within the hours of daylight, those of other species during twilight or during the hours of darkness.

label.value: behaviour of crepuscular and nocturnal species

value.value: Among species that show crepuscular/nocturnal activity, some are most active for brief periods at dusk or at dusk and dawn.

definition.value: It may be that, in nature, the gradual changes in light intensity around sunset and dawn play some part in the expression of activity at those times; however, the persistance E, M and Nd peaks in constant darkness and in constant dim light shows that endogenous mechanisms are involved.

label.value: behaviour of male and virgin female

value.value: The behaviours of male and virgin female mosquitoes relate principally to mating and feeding on plant juices. Flight periodicities recorded in the laboratory for four species were characterized by bursts of activity at dusk and, to a lesser extent, dawn with scotophase activity present or not, according to species.

In the laboratory, in most of the four nocturnal/crepuscular species investigated, insemination led to a reduction in the E and M flight-activity peaks shown by virgin femlaes and an increase in scotophase activity. Such a periodicity was characteristic of wild females of all these species taken in biting catches.

label.value: behaviour of blood-fed, gravid and parous female

value.value: Inseminated females that have taken a full blood meal are characteristically inactive during the first stages of vitellogenesis, although they may fly to obtain nectar. Flight activity is resumed once they are gravid.

WIld females exhibit peaks of alighting on vertebrate hosts and of oviposition at the beginning and end of the photophase. Captive females show a similar bimodal pattern with regard to flight activity, sugar feeding, response to host odour, and oviposition. When continuously exposed to sugar or host odour captive females showed significant levels of activity throughout the scotophase.
